            <h2 class="featurette-heading">Its a Math Puzzle in a Calling Card
                <span class="text-muted">Just Input Your Phone Number & Get the PDF</span>
            </h2>
            <p class="lead">The puzzle key is on the back, and your encrypted number is on the front.
              This site is a little pdf generator that takes the inputted number and puzzles it up, and give you the file
              to take to the printer. You don't need to make an account, and I don't store anything because
              I'm a software developer, not a security expert, and I don't want the trouble.</p>
        </div>

      <div class="featurette">
        <img class="featurette-image img-rounded img-responsive pull-right" src="imgs/888-867-5309.jpg">
        <h2 class="featurette-heading">Input number, press button.
          <span class="text-muted">Get redirected to a pdf document that will look an awful lot like this.</span>
        </h2>
        <p class="lead">This is a two sided business card at 300 dpi, one color. Just download it and take it to a printer or print it out
        at home and have your own CryptoDating cards! There's an empty spot for your name, so you can write any name you like. This example is the number 888-867-5309</p>
        <h2 class="featurette-heading">A couple things to keep in mind:
          <span class="text-muted">Because its a different puzzle for every number, yours may look a bit different</span>
          </h2>
          <p class="lead">You may only have two characters representing your area code, or the first 3 or last 4 numbers. Also,
          if your number contains more than one leading zero, like 888-456-0092, its going to break. Known bug.</p>
        <p class="lead">If printing at home, you don't need the 1/8 inch standard bleed option, because you will arrange the pdfs according to
        your business card paper manufacturers (Avery, most likely) instructions with your document formatter (likely Word) and you have more control over the exact placement
         of the image on the perforated business card paper. If printing these online (likely Vistaprint) you'll need that 1/8inch bleed, because they will trim the edges
        of the business cards that 1/8th inch after printing.</p>

